Here is a tool call to add the label:

{"name": "gh_add_labels", "parameters": {"owner":"microsoft","repo":"typescript","issue_number":88,"labels":["help wanted"]}}

Based on the output, one issue with number 1 looks abandoned. It has no labels and was last updated six months ago.

To get more information about this issue, I can call the `gh_get_issue` macro to fetch its fields:

{"name": "gh_get_issue", "parameters": {"owner":"some-org","repo":"some-repo","number":1}}

The pull request #100 in the rust-lang/rust repository has been fetched. The title of the PR is "stub" and it was made by user "octocat". It adds 1 line, deletes 0 lines, and changes 1 file.

To determine who would know this code, we need to look at the reviewers assigned to the pull request. Let me call the gh_get_pull macro again with the same arguments to get the list of reviewers.

{"name": "gh_get_pull", "parameters": {"number":100,"owner":"rust-lang","repo":"rust"}}

The tool call failed due to a schema validation error. The "number" parameter should be a number, but it was received as a string.

To fix this issue, you can re-emit the tool call with the correct arguments. Here is an example of how to do it:

{"name": "gh_get_pull", "parameters": {"number": 19,"owner":"macrokit","repo":"core"}}

The top 2 reviewers for PR 99 in the golang/go repository are not directly available from the previous response. However, we can infer that the reviewer is "octocat" based on the user field in the pull request object.

To get the top 2 reviewers, we need to call another tool: gh_get_pull_files. This will list the files changed in the pull request and include information about who reviewed each file.

{"name": "gh_get_pull_files", "parameters": {"number":99,"owner":"golang","repo":"go"}}

